WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.360
Hi, my name is Sean.

00:00:09.360 --> 00:00:12.200
I'm a product manager at RStudio.

00:00:12.200 --> 00:00:17.160
As a product manager, I get to talk to data science teams, both small and large, all over

00:00:17.160 --> 00:00:18.160
the world.

00:00:18.160 --> 00:00:23.400
And unfortunately, in interacting with these teams, we often hear that they're confronted

00:00:23.400 --> 00:00:27.840
by a false choice to either pick R or Python.

00:00:27.840 --> 00:00:33.279
This choice might occur when they're writing a job description to hire a new data scientist.

00:00:33.279 --> 00:00:39.680
It might occur when they're trying to decide what to learn as individuals who want to upskill

00:00:39.680 --> 00:00:44.660
themselves, or it might occur when they're interacting with IT, asking for resources

00:00:44.660 --> 00:00:46.900
to support a project.

00:00:46.900 --> 00:00:49.520
So why do teams face this false choice?

00:00:49.520 --> 00:00:53.439
Do we really need to pick between one language or another?

00:00:53.439 --> 00:00:55.040
Well, the answer is no.

00:00:55.040 --> 00:00:56.520
And today we're going to talk about why.

00:00:57.320 --> 00:01:01.080
We're going to look at some of the common myths that lead to this choice, how to debunk

00:01:01.080 --> 00:01:06.160
those myths, and ultimately how data science teams can be most effective when they choose

00:01:06.160 --> 00:01:08.519
to use R and Python together.

00:01:08.519 --> 00:01:15.360
Now, to set some context, imagine you're a craftsman, someone who is handy and builds

00:01:15.360 --> 00:01:16.360
things.

00:01:16.360 --> 00:01:18.639
As a craftsman, you'd probably be familiar with screwdrivers.

00:01:18.639 --> 00:01:22.519
I mean, who hasn't used a screwdriver to put something together?

00:01:23.239 --> 00:01:27.199
And you might be aware that screwdrivers come in a variety of different shapes and forms.

00:01:27.199 --> 00:01:33.680
You can have a flathead screwdriver, a star bit, a Phillips head, and each of these screwdrivers

00:01:33.680 --> 00:01:36.839
is designed to serve a specific purpose.

00:01:36.839 --> 00:01:40.720
Now imagine as a craftsman, if you were told that you have to choose for the rest of your

00:01:40.720 --> 00:01:47.919
career between using one type of screwdriver or another, you'd probably look at that person

00:01:47.919 --> 00:01:49.320
and say, that's crazy.

00:01:49.320 --> 00:01:51.839
There's no way I can practically make this choice.

00:01:51.839 --> 00:01:53.639
For some projects, I'm going to need a flathead.

00:01:53.639 --> 00:01:55.440
For other projects, I'll need a Phillips.

00:01:55.440 --> 00:02:00.400
It doesn't make sense for me to pick one screwdriver to use for the rest of my career.

00:02:00.400 --> 00:02:08.080
Instead, what you might do as a craftsman is to say, I want to opt in to using a smarter

00:02:08.080 --> 00:02:13.839
tool, a tool that's going to be more powerful and allow me to take advantage of all these

00:02:13.839 --> 00:02:16.279
different bits that are out there.

00:02:16.279 --> 00:02:21.839
Specifically, as a craftsman, you might be interested in something like a drill, a tool

00:02:21.839 --> 00:02:27.479
that regardless of what bit you're going to need for a project, allows you to work faster

00:02:27.479 --> 00:02:33.199
and to accomplish more and allows you to work in an easier fashion.

00:02:33.199 --> 00:02:36.119
So craftsmen have this drill.

00:02:36.119 --> 00:02:37.679
What about data science teams?

00:02:37.679 --> 00:02:44.559
Well, I believe as data scientists, we should refuse that same false choice between R and

00:02:44.600 --> 00:02:50.320
Python and other languages, just as the craftsman refuses to pick one type of screwdriver.

00:02:50.320 --> 00:02:56.960
Instead, we should work alongside of folks in IT and the leaders of our teams to build

00:02:56.960 --> 00:03:01.679
something like a drill, something that regardless of what language we use, is going to give

00:03:01.679 --> 00:03:06.039
us the power to accomplish our projects faster and easier.

00:03:06.039 --> 00:03:09.440
So what is that drill for data science?

00:03:09.440 --> 00:03:11.279
We'll take a look at that in a second.

00:03:11.320 --> 00:03:15.440
But first, I want to address some of these common objections that you'll hear.

00:03:15.440 --> 00:03:19.759
People that say, no, no, no, there's no such thing as a drill for data science.

00:03:19.759 --> 00:03:24.639
We have to pick a single language or a single screwdriver.

00:03:24.639 --> 00:03:26.240
So where do these objections come from?

00:03:26.240 --> 00:03:29.559
What's the biggest objection that data science teams face?

00:03:29.559 --> 00:03:34.919
Well, the first one is this belief that if we are to support more than one language,

00:03:34.919 --> 00:03:39.440
we'll end up doing a lot of duplicative work.

00:03:39.559 --> 00:03:45.240
So for example, if I were a team that wanted to use R and Python, IT might be worried that

00:03:45.240 --> 00:03:48.080
now I have two times the amount of work to do.

00:03:48.080 --> 00:03:51.320
Instead of supporting one language, I now have to support two.

00:03:51.320 --> 00:03:56.440
That means twice the number of installs, twice the number of support tickets, twice the money

00:03:56.440 --> 00:03:59.839
spent on IT resources.

00:03:59.839 --> 00:04:03.720
And luckily, this line of thinking simply isn't accurate.

00:04:03.720 --> 00:04:09.399
The reason for that is because regardless of what language you use, the core things

00:04:09.399 --> 00:04:12.399
that IT needs to support are the same.

00:04:12.399 --> 00:04:18.480
Things like computation, logs, authentication, security, data access.

00:04:18.480 --> 00:04:24.000
These provide a common core, that drill, that we can invest in regardless of which drill

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:27.079
bit, which language, we end up using.

00:04:27.079 --> 00:04:31.600
So I want to show you some of those tools that we've worked on at RStudio to make that

00:04:31.600 --> 00:04:38.399
type of underlying investment, that core of data science infrastructure, accessible.

00:04:38.399 --> 00:04:42.079
So the first thing I want to take a look at is in the development space.

00:04:42.079 --> 00:04:47.019
When we're data scientists going to write code in either R or Python, often what we

00:04:47.019 --> 00:04:51.600
want is to choose an editor that's purpose-built for one of those languages.

00:04:51.600 --> 00:04:54.079
So in R, that might be the RStudio IDE.

00:04:54.079 --> 00:04:58.440
In Python, that might be something like a Jupyter Notebook, or more recently, Jupyter

00:04:58.440 --> 00:05:04.440
Labs, or perhaps I want to use a full-fledged development environment like VS Code.

00:05:04.440 --> 00:05:09.399
Now IT might be thinking, oh no, that means we have to support all these different editors,

00:05:09.399 --> 00:05:11.160
all these different environments.

00:05:11.160 --> 00:05:12.880
But luckily, that's not true.

00:05:12.880 --> 00:05:19.420
With tools like RStudio Server Pro, you can install a single infrastructure that supports

00:05:19.420 --> 00:05:20.839
those different editors.

00:05:20.839 --> 00:05:24.519
And so what you're seeing on the screen here is the homepage of RStudio Server.

00:05:25.079 --> 00:05:29.519
When a data scientist enters through that common front door, they're able to pick the

00:05:29.519 --> 00:05:32.880
different editors that they might want to use for a certain project.

00:05:32.880 --> 00:05:38.480
So IT only has to stand up one server environment, they only have to do one set of configuration,

00:05:38.480 --> 00:05:43.239
they only have to supply data access to one common entry point, but a data scientist is

00:05:43.239 --> 00:05:47.839
still able to use whatever editor makes the most sense for their project.

00:05:47.839 --> 00:05:53.720
You'll also see here that we're taking advantage of cloud-native tools like Kubernetes to provide

00:05:53.720 --> 00:06:00.000
elastic scale, and a Docker backend to provide explicitly those dependencies that we might

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:01.760
need for a project.

00:06:01.760 --> 00:06:06.000
So what this all amounts to is that in development, we're able to get to our first line of code

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:10.920
really quickly, regardless of what language that line of code is written in, without doubling

00:06:10.920 --> 00:06:12.720
the IT headaches.

00:06:12.720 --> 00:06:13.959
Now that's development.

00:06:13.959 --> 00:06:14.959
What about production?

00:06:14.959 --> 00:06:20.399
What about when it comes time to create these different artifacts and share those with others?

00:06:20.399 --> 00:06:23.640
Well, luckily, the same concept applies.

00:06:23.679 --> 00:06:28.359
So at RStudio, what that looks like is a tool like RStudio Connect.

00:06:28.359 --> 00:06:34.519
So RStudio Connect allows you to deploy a wide variety of data artifacts, regardless

00:06:34.519 --> 00:06:36.679
of what language they're written in.

00:06:36.679 --> 00:06:41.279
So for web applications in R, that might be something like Shiny.

00:06:41.279 --> 00:06:46.440
For web applications in Python, that might be something like Dash, Streamlit, or Bokeh.

00:06:46.440 --> 00:06:51.559
But regardless of which of those engines you choose to use, RStudio Connect allows you

00:06:51.559 --> 00:06:56.160
to quickly deploy them onto a web server so that you get a URL that you can share with

00:06:56.160 --> 00:06:57.160
others.

00:06:57.160 --> 00:07:02.640
And Connect takes care of things like authentication, security, logging, and scale.

00:07:02.640 --> 00:07:07.559
Similarly, if you wanted to create an API, say you have a model that you want to expose

00:07:07.559 --> 00:07:13.480
to other services, well, that exposure might take place in R through a package like Plumber,

00:07:13.480 --> 00:07:16.359
or might take place in Python through a tool like Flask.

00:07:16.760 --> 00:07:22.119
But either way, Connect provides that common core infrastructure, that drill.

00:07:22.119 --> 00:07:26.160
Finally, the same thing applies for automated reporting.

00:07:26.160 --> 00:07:28.799
So in the Python side, that might be Jupyter Notebooks.

00:07:28.799 --> 00:07:31.359
On the R side, it might be something like R Markdown.

00:07:31.359 --> 00:07:35.160
Regardless, again, we're able to deploy those things to Connect.

00:07:35.160 --> 00:07:39.720
And Connect can handle things like scheduling those notebooks to be re-rendered on a regular

00:07:39.720 --> 00:07:46.200
basis, emailing stakeholders with the new results, and even customizing those emails

00:07:46.200 --> 00:07:50.640
so that you can send exactly what you need to a stakeholder's inbox, regardless of what

00:07:50.640 --> 00:07:52.519
language you're using for a project.

00:07:52.519 --> 00:07:56.679
And again, IT is only setting up this infrastructure once.

00:07:56.679 --> 00:08:02.239
They're not doubling their work just because you're multiplying by five or tenfold the

00:08:02.239 --> 00:08:04.320
number of different data products that you can use.

00:08:04.320 --> 00:08:07.920
And as a data scientist, that flexibility is key.

00:08:07.920 --> 00:08:12.320
When it comes to communicate your work, getting buy-in to the modeling that you're doing,

00:08:12.320 --> 00:08:17.440
or working alongside of a domain expert in real time in a meeting, you need to have the

00:08:17.440 --> 00:08:23.239
flexibility to use all these different tools to be an effective data science team.

00:08:23.239 --> 00:08:28.559
And so that's what we're setting out to do, is to build products, build those drills that

00:08:28.559 --> 00:08:33.400
allow you, regardless of drill bit, to effectively communicate your work.

00:08:33.400 --> 00:08:37.640
And so because this is so important, because it is the most common myth, I want to spend

00:08:37.640 --> 00:08:42.880
just a little bit more time looking at that common core.

00:08:42.880 --> 00:08:48.599
And so this diagram hopefully shows you what I've been talking about, where we have these

00:08:48.599 --> 00:08:53.200
layers that are going to be the same regardless of what language we're using.

00:08:53.200 --> 00:09:00.479
So those layers are things like common authentication, things like logging, things like scaling.

00:09:00.479 --> 00:09:07.919
And then the final layer, the choice of R or Python, is ultimately a last mile effort.

00:09:07.919 --> 00:09:10.479
So we're not multiplying our work by two.

00:09:10.479 --> 00:09:14.479
We're actually only changing that final top piece.

00:09:14.479 --> 00:09:19.320
Now I showed you RStudio Server Pro and RStudio Connect as one way to implement this drill.

00:09:19.320 --> 00:09:22.520
But teams can implement the drill in other ways as well.

00:09:22.520 --> 00:09:26.400
For example, some organizations will use a cloud provider.

00:09:26.400 --> 00:09:29.280
Some organizations will use something like Docker.

00:09:29.280 --> 00:09:35.760
Regardless, the key concept is that you build those common paradigms that your data scientist,

00:09:35.760 --> 00:09:40.880
regardless of language or package, is going to be able to take advantage of.

00:09:40.880 --> 00:09:48.039
And once you debunk that myth that more languages mean more problems, you're well on your way

00:09:48.039 --> 00:09:53.400
to those multiplicative efforts to avoiding that false choice and having a lot more options

00:09:53.400 --> 00:09:56.599
to build what you need to build to get the job done.

00:09:56.599 --> 00:09:59.359
So that's that first myth, hopefully now debunked.

00:09:59.359 --> 00:10:04.840
Let's talk about a second one, which is that multilingual teams can't collaborate.

00:10:04.840 --> 00:10:10.719
Imagine you are a data science team leader, and you have three or four data scientists

00:10:10.719 --> 00:10:14.880
on your team that have built out something really awesome in Python.

00:10:14.880 --> 00:10:20.000
In fact, I was speaking to a data science team leader named Wayne recently,

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:22.280
who was exactly in this situation.

00:10:22.280 --> 00:10:24.960
But he needed to hire someone new.

00:10:25.080 --> 00:10:27.719
His context was a marketing project.

00:10:27.719 --> 00:10:31.440
He really wanted to hire someone with marketing domain knowledge.

00:10:31.440 --> 00:10:36.520
But unfortunately, he couldn't find that candidate who had both the Python expertise

00:10:36.520 --> 00:10:38.280
and the marketing background.

00:10:38.280 --> 00:10:43.200
But he did know a few people who had strong marketing chops and knew a little bit of R.

00:10:43.200 --> 00:10:45.640
Is he presented with a false choice here?

00:10:45.640 --> 00:10:51.280
I think so, because it turns out that even if your code base is mostly in Python,

00:10:51.280 --> 00:10:56.159
you can bring someone who has a background in R up to speed really quickly.

00:10:56.159 --> 00:11:00.400
And again, it comes down to having those right tools, a common drill bit,

00:11:00.400 --> 00:11:04.400
to allow for that type of inter-team collaboration.

00:11:04.400 --> 00:11:07.919
And so I want to quickly show you what investments we've made in RStudio

00:11:07.919 --> 00:11:11.400
to make that type of collaboration possible.

00:11:11.400 --> 00:11:15.119
So what we're looking at here is the RStudio IDE.

00:11:15.119 --> 00:11:18.719
And the new version of the IDE has a what-you-see-is-what-you-mean editor

00:11:18.719 --> 00:11:20.039
for R Markdown.

00:11:20.039 --> 00:11:25.080
And inside of that editor, you're able to incorporate both R and Python code chunks.

00:11:25.080 --> 00:11:28.679
So here you're looking at Python code that we're able to run,

00:11:28.679 --> 00:11:32.280
but that code takes advantage of objects coming from R.

00:11:32.280 --> 00:11:35.359
See the r.cars object.

00:11:35.359 --> 00:11:39.919
So once we have that Python code executed, it's actually going to write objects back

00:11:39.919 --> 00:11:42.359
into the environment that we can see in the IDE.

00:11:42.359 --> 00:11:47.760
So in the environment pane in the object explorer, we can view that pandas dataframe we created.

00:11:47.799 --> 00:11:50.599
Once we're happy with the result that we have in Python,

00:11:50.599 --> 00:11:55.200
we can use the what-you-see-is-what-you-mean editor to insert an R code chunk

00:11:55.200 --> 00:11:58.000
that takes advantage of that Python dataframe.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:03.599
So just like we used the R object in Python, we can use the Python object in R

00:12:03.599 --> 00:12:07.479
and create a plot with ggplot2 of that Python data.

00:12:07.479 --> 00:12:12.359
Now, this interoperability extends beyond R Markdown through the reticulate package.

00:12:12.359 --> 00:12:16.919
So here we have a shiny application that's going to take a Python function

00:12:16.919 --> 00:12:22.119
and actually source it and make it available to the R engine without any conversion.

00:12:22.119 --> 00:12:23.599
It's pretty magical.

00:12:23.599 --> 00:12:27.000
We can then call that Python function inside of our shiny app,

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:29.960
and that allows us to build something like this,

00:12:29.960 --> 00:12:36.200
which is a shiny application where the front end, all the input and controls are driven by shiny,

00:12:36.200 --> 00:12:40.239
but the backend simulation is occurring in those Python functions.

00:12:40.239 --> 00:12:45.159
So we're able, as a multilingual team, to really glue these two things together,

00:12:45.159 --> 00:12:46.840
whether we're bilingual or not.

00:12:46.840 --> 00:12:53.080
We can take advantage of a code base written in either language to achieve a really unique outcome.

00:12:53.080 --> 00:12:56.440
And that's what debunking these false choices is all about.

00:12:56.440 --> 00:13:01.000
It's finding ways to combine the strengths, the best of both languages,

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:06.440
as well as the best of our team to come together to create something faster and easier

00:13:06.440 --> 00:13:10.239
than we could if we were in isolated silos with either language.

00:13:10.239 --> 00:13:12.880
And that leads me to my final point,

00:13:12.880 --> 00:13:19.479
which is that we need, as data scientists, to optimize for people, not for tools.

00:13:19.479 --> 00:13:20.719
What do I mean by that?

00:13:20.719 --> 00:13:25.400
Well, think about the story of Wayne trying to hire, as it turned out, her name was Vicky,

00:13:25.400 --> 00:13:30.440
a data scientist coming from the R space instead of the Python background.

00:13:30.440 --> 00:13:34.719
Because Wayne was able to set aside the distinction in tools,

00:13:34.719 --> 00:13:38.679
he could come up with a data science team that together was more effective

00:13:38.679 --> 00:13:43.400
than if he had limited his job criteria to only people that knew Python.

00:13:43.400 --> 00:13:46.559
And so we see that story play out time and time again.

00:13:46.559 --> 00:13:49.799
At the end of the day, when we talk to data science team leaders,

00:13:49.799 --> 00:13:55.520
their most important asset and their most expensive isn't a particular tool or platform.

00:13:55.520 --> 00:14:00.080
It's the data scientists that they're hiring to solve complex problems.

00:14:00.080 --> 00:14:05.400
Said another way, one of the big reasons organizations invest in data science in the first place

00:14:05.400 --> 00:14:11.320
is because black box solutions like Tableau or Power BI simply don't meet the needs

00:14:11.320 --> 00:14:15.679
of the rich, complex real world problems that they're facing.

00:14:15.679 --> 00:14:19.640
So why would it make any sense for those same data science teams

00:14:19.640 --> 00:14:24.239
that have recognized they need the flexibility and power of code to achieve outcomes

00:14:24.239 --> 00:14:28.400
to then sabotage themselves by limiting themselves to only one language?

00:14:28.400 --> 00:14:31.200
It simply doesn't. It's a false choice.

00:14:31.200 --> 00:14:37.760
And so today, my final plea is to pick the people that will make your data science team effective

00:14:37.760 --> 00:14:40.039
and then supply them with what they need.

00:14:40.039 --> 00:14:42.679
Don't make people subservient to tools.

00:14:42.679 --> 00:14:44.119
It should be the other way around.

00:14:44.119 --> 00:14:48.320
Allow data science teams to pick whatever language or tools can be most effective.

00:14:48.320 --> 00:14:53.239
And to help you do that at RStudio, we've invested in building out drills

00:14:53.239 --> 00:14:59.159
so that regardless of what drill bit you need, you can effectively build something faster and easier.

00:14:59.159 --> 00:15:02.039
Thank you so much for your time, and I look forward to your questions.

